5262,"Update many in mongoose

I have a very simple case. I want to update my collection every midnight.
All I want to do, is to loop over every document in my collection (Users) and then if User.created is false, I want to turn it into true.
How to do it in mongoose? Thanks!
Edit: The story is very simple, I just want to iterate over every element in my db using mongoose and if iterated element has field ""created"" === false, change it to true.

,Multithreading and Synchronization: JavaScript interpreters are single-threaded, so while GWT silently accepts the synchronized keyword, it has no real effect. Synchronization-related library methods are not available, including Object.wait(), Object.notify(), and Object.notifyAll(). The compiler will ignore the synchronized keyword but will refuse to compile your code if the Objects related synchronization methods are invoked. Please read http://www.gwtproject.org/doc/latest/DevGuideCodingBasicsCompatibility.html","Embed Field: Update many in mongoose

5274,"Mongo - Are the ObjectIds of duplicate documents different?

So I was trying to understand how ObjectId's are created in Mongo, and I found this page describing it:
<pre><code>a 4-byte value representing the seconds since the Unix epoch,
a 3-byte counter, starting with a random value.
Because of the timestamps, does this then mean that even an inserted documents with the same exact contents into the database would get assigned two different `ObjectIds'?

,@Achshar so, also a tip for job interviews - it's ok to extend a class. for example, a good answer of ""how to count an array with O(1)"" is to just keep a count data memeber.","Embed Field: Mongo - Are the ObjectIds of duplicate documents different?

So I was trying to understand how ObjectId's are created in Mongo, and I found this page describing it:
<pre><code>a 4-byte value representing the seconds since the Unix epoch,
a 3-byte counter, starting with a random value.
Because of the timestamps, does this then mean that even an inserted documents with the same exact contents into the database would get assigned two different `ObjectIds'?
